The State of the Dogs on WeRateDogs¶

The WeRateDogs Twitter feed, @dog_rates, is a destination for dog owners and lovers to come together and evaluate dogs.

The dog owners normally post a photo or video of their dog, with a caption including a rating of the dog. This is not just any rating. The dogs on WeRateDogs are no ordinary dogs, with the average dog exceeding a 10/10. Only the very terrible score below a 10, and ratings as high as 1776 have been seen. The dog owners may also add a "dog stage", ranging from "puppo" to "doggo" and everything in between.

The dog lovers view the dogs and express their reactions in the forms of likes, retweets, and comments. This analysis will focus on the likes as a better indicator of pup-ularity. (Sorry, can't resist).

Dog Stage Popularity¶

According to the Dogtionary, a #WeRateDogs book, dogs come in many stages:

  • Doggo, a big pupper
  • Pupper, a small doggo
  • Puppo, somewhere in between
  • Floofer, An exceptionally fluffy dog

Do dog owners and dog lovers have a preference for one dog stage over another?

Dog Stages: Ratings¶

In [80]:

Pupper by far is the most common dog stage.

Question: Is pupper the most commonly posted dog stage because puppers are more likely to get higher ratings?

Insight: The analyises below show that puppers, although the most common, actually have lower ratings and fewer likes.

Note: One might argue the sample size of some of the less common dog stages may skew their ratings. Regardless, all of the other stages, including the second most common doggo and third most common puppo stages, surpass the pupper stage in ratings, likes, and retweets.

Puppers tie for the lowest median rating numerator. Note that several categories have less than 10 posts (doggo-pupper, floofer, and doggo-puppo). Among the more common categories, doggo and puppo, puppers still underperform.

In [83]:

Visually we can see the the majority of pupper ratings lag behind the other stages.

Dog Stages: Favorites and Rewteets¶

If we thought perhaps the users posting the puppers are just modest, giving their dogs lower ratings, we would be wrong. Judging by the median number of likes and retweets, a reflection of the opinion of the twitter audience, puppers still come in last.

Among the top three most common dog stages, the average pupperhas less than half as many likes as the doggo and less than one third as many likes as the puppo. The retweet ratios are similar.

Good dogs, great dogs¶

For a sense of just how great and just how horrible these dogs can get, let's look at the dogs with the most and least number of likes.

Question: What is the range of likeability of these dogs?

Insight: The dogs on WeRateDogs range from good to great. Even the least liked dog could be considered pretty popular. There are some tweets with very low ratings, but a visual assessment of the text quickly clarifies that the ratings are due to the users or disatisfaction with the absence of dogs in a given photo.

The favorite dog¶

The most liked dog is a puppo, receiving 139,582 favorites. The predicted breed was inconclusive, with an accuracy rating of 20%. Interestingly, the most liked dog does not have the highest rating. Later we will explore the extent to which ratings, favorites, and retweets are correlated.

The lowest rated dogs¶

Looking at the least liked did not yield any hideous pictures. Perhaps the posts rated lowest by the users will.

Neiter of the lowest rated have photos of dogs recognizable by the neural network. Looking at the tweet texts, one was a user calling out plagiarism, and the other has no dog in the image. In both cases, it was users, not the dogs, that disappointed.

The plagiarized tweet is also a note of caution for using favorite_count to measure dog popularity. It was likely the message about plagiarizing that generated the likes.

Users versus the audience¶

Question: Is there a correlation between how users rate their dogs and how the Twitter audience reacts?

Insight: After removing outliers in the rating_numerator, there appears to be a moderate positive relationship between rating_numerator on the one hand and retweet_count and favorite_count on the other. This suggests that there is some agreement as to what makes a good dog in the WeRateDogs universe, but that users also use this space for creative expression and fun, rather than just a strict assessment of dogs.

Retweet and favorite counts are not surprisingly correlated (0.93). When including the full range of rating_numerators, there is no correlation between rating numerator and favorite or retweet count. This may be due to a couple factors:

  • The ratings are given by the user posting the dog whereas the retweets and favorites reflect the audience's reaction.
  • The rating system is subjective: Most ratings range from 10 to 14 - as high or higher than the denominator. There is not a single rubric defining these ratings, leaving it up to the interpretation of the user. There are also some very large ratings that users self-elected to assign their dogs.

Let's explore the dataset visually, focusing on the more standard ratings below 15:

In [134]:

If we remove the rating outliers, we see that the correlation between ratings and favorites increases from 0.02 to 0.41. The relationship also appears to be non-linear, with ratings below ten receiving fewer than 30,000 favorites, and favorites increasing as ratings rise from 10 to 14.

Conclusions and Further Reserach¶

As we can see even the least favorited dog is not a bad dog at all, because

they're good dogs Brent

— WeRateDogs™ (@dog_rates) September 12, 2016

The impact of user popularity

Further research should take into account users' followers. Controling for the number of followers a user has would help us account for the impact potential viewers has on likes and retweets. Another way to address the connection between user popularity and dog popularity would be to compare different dogs posted by the same user, or an A/A test by having different users post the same dog tweet.

Are there really any bad dogs on WeRateDogs?

The lowest rated dogs were due to either not containing dogs or to unethical behavior on the users part. The top dogs after all were marching for their moms. A deeper analysis of the texts of dogs rated below a 10 could reveal whether these are isolated cases or a trend in the community.

Understanding the WeRateDogs community

As we all know, they're all good dogs. To rise among the ranks, however, dogs may need to go beyond just looking cute and display some inner virtues. Looking at the numer one tweet, for example, reveals dogs that were committed enough to go on a march with their moms. An A/B test could be conducted by posting the same dog photo with different tweet content. Can the same dog improve its likes by getting off the counts and doing getting involved in a good cause?
